{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/implementation/07-frontend/","result":{"data":{"logo":null,"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1>Why a Desktop App?</h1>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>More real estate,</li>\n<li>Higher security (unless you like <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-kills-the-great-suspender-heres-what-you-should-do-next/\">all of your passwords leaked on the dark web</a>)</li>\n<li>Naturally suitable for more serious, administrative functionality</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Possibly higher development time</li>\n<li>We might need access to the user’s browser cookies, to scrape data out of VoiceFlow</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This was always known to us yet, in earlier HCI iterations <a href=\"../../hci/2-prototype-1\">HERE</a>, we were first considering designing a browser extension. The reason was that we thought we would need to reverse engineer VoiceFlow’s API. And we did that. But as mentioned <a href=\"../../research/4-reverse-engineering-voiceflow-2\">HERE</a>, eventually that wasn’t necessary. So we defaulted back to a desktop app, which could arguably be more difficult to develop.</p>\n<h1>How Did You Build The Frontend?</h1>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 2000px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/98e2c/electron.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 15.4%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"electron\"\n        title=\"electron\"\n        src=\"/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/f97d7/electron.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/0eb09/electron.png 500w,\n/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/1263b/electron.png 1000w,\n/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/f97d7/electron.png 2000w,\n/static/038996a89f3697e00aff55d2b4dcc9be/98e2c/electron.png 2400w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>The core framework we use is Electron. It essentially is a browser instance running a locally hosted website trying to look like a native app. </p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use any web UI framework and therefore benefit from many open source projects</li>\n<li>Provide installers for nearly any platform (Win, MacOS, Linux)</li>\n<li>Looks like a native app</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Non-native performance (not important in our case)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Our first UI iteration was an implementation of our Figma prototypes, built using pure HTML and CSS since we were familiar with these technologies. It was very simple but gave us a decent foundation to build off of.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 2000px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/cd15d/react.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 33.599999999999994%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"react\"\n        title=\"react\"\n        src=\"/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/f97d7/react.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/0eb09/react.png 500w,\n/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/1263b/react.png 1000w,\n/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/f97d7/react.png 2000w,\n/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/49142/react.png 3000w,\n/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/1ce76/react.png 4000w,\n/static/4ade5cac5aba1b2a6129e12ce9a93deb/cd15d/react.png 5000w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>For a particular UI framework, we chose <code class=\"language-text\">React</code>. It allows us to design our website in a component-driven way, similar to an Object Oriented Model. This way we could reuse a lot of the previous code we had and be more flexible in implementing changes without having to rewrite core parts of the codebase. </p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 2000px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/6bde6/mobx.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 35.4%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"mobx\"\n        title=\"mobx\"\n        src=\"/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/f97d7/mobx.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/0eb09/mobx.png 500w,\n/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/1263b/mobx.png 1000w,\n/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/f97d7/mobx.png 2000w,\n/static/a7d8618c760b77c849e74bd8942dea47/6bde6/mobx.png 2100w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Our app has state shared across all pages. Usually this is a hassle to properly deal with in <code class=\"language-text\">react</code> and ensure all data dependencies are updated. This is why we chose <code class=\"language-text\">mobx</code> to design our data model. <code class=\"language-text\">mobx</code> allows us to declare which objects are system state, and it handles the responsibility of properly updating anything that might depend on that state. </p>\n<p>Take a look at the actual screen designs HERE LINK.</p>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"h1","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Why a Desktop App?"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Advantages:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"More real estate,"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Higher security (unless you like "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-kills-the-great-suspender-heres-what-you-should-do-next/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"all of your passwords leaked on the dark web"}]},{"type":"text","value":")"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Naturally suitable for more serious, administrative functionality"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":